column1: 8302868,AI,2023-09-25T11:06:50Z,high,"High value habitat. Major work has been done on this crossing to backwater the outlet using driven sheet pilings. There is an approximate 1.2 m high drop following 40 m of stream after the outlet where adult coho spawners are staged. Incredible spawning habitat upstream with low gradients and abundant gravels. Structure has the date 1920 stamped on the inlet. Known coho spawning system with long history and the Chicago creek restoration society putting in work for over 20 years. column1: 8302869,AI,2023-09-25T13:35:25Z,high,"Very high value habitat upstream with pockets of gravel throughout. Adult cutthroat or rainbow observed just downstream of Highway 16 crossing upstream of here. Structure is dated 1923. Water flows within the box. Culvert at the time of the survey was approximately two to 5 cm deep. Skeena fisheries commission site with recommendation for installation of baffles. Fill depth estimated at 30 m and culvert length at 120 m, but changed to 9.9 and 99, respectively, in order to fulfill provincial sumbission requirements.",Although ancient the structure appears to be in good condition with no evidence of erosion or embankment issues. The concrete wing walls on the downstream side are cracked on the river right bank.          ,Absolutely massive amount of fill on top of the structure.  Flood would likely just back up the water until it could drain.          ,Installation of baffles within this structure seems very doable and a prudent move by Canadian national. Not sure why this hasnt happened yet. column1: 8800026,AI,2023-09-26T10:06:21Z,high,High value spawning habitat upstream. One redd observed upstream. DFO and MOTI historic back watering and side channel sites. column1: 8800149,AI,2023-09-26T14:11:58Z,low,"Major debris accumulation downstream of the culvert. Stream is dewatered downstream for at least 60 m. There are numerous buried concrete lock blocks downstream of the outlet which may have been part of a backwatering system. Trash rack upstream of the crossing has failed, with steel members scattered throughout the stream. There are poured concrete wing walls upstream of the crossing with the right bank being approximately 8 m long and river left bank wall at 30 m long. Bottom half of the culvert is concrete and the top half is corrugated metal. Steeper stream with step pool habitat and bedrock throughout the channel. Dolly Varden and cutthroat noted upstream in FISS.","Strange structure but seems to be holding up OK. River right bank has failed a string of the wing wall with large chunks of rock falling into the channel. Steel trash rock upstream has failed with steel members scattered throughout the channel. Theres a large amount of accumulated debris downstream of the outlet. Numerous concrete block blocks are located downstream with many of them buried, potentially indicating a historic back watering project          "," The concrete arm ring of the stream banks, upstream of the pike, likely reduce the chance of a flood event, causing a failure to the structure. Large high power stream, however, could move a lot of material to block the pipe.",  Dolly Varden and cutthroat noted upstream in FISS. Large amount of bedrock upstream would make construction difficult and stream.  Seems unstable with large amounts of debris moving. Highway 16 so very busy expensive to work on.,2351,,,,,,,8800149,,newgraph_airvine,newgraph_airvine,327,Tributary to Skeena River,Highway 16,,MOTI,Closed Bottom Structure,Round Culvert,,3.5,35,,2023-09-26,9,539719,6083274,No,,No,No,,4,0,1.4,No,14,10,10,No,No,Shallow Fill,Medium,,,10,,,,,,,phase1,,,newgraph_airvine,3,1,1,5,4,4,16,21,10,9,2,1,10,3,35,56,20230926_142254.jpg,20230926_142307.jpg,20230926_142319.jpg,20230926_142311.jpg,20230926_142257.jpg,20230926_142314.jpg,20230926_142351.jpg,,,20230926_142356.jpg,,,,,"<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC ""-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0//EN"" ""http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-html40/strict.dtd"">

column1: 8801343,AI,2023-09-26T11:38:36Z,medium,"Small drainage with 1 m high beaver dam approximately 5 m upstream of the inlet. Fine substrate. Seems unlikely that the stream is fish bearing. Pipe slope estimated as deformed pipe and position made measurement with clinometer not possible.",Lots of beaver activity immediately upstream plus deposition of fines upstream causing blockage issues. There is some significant erosion around the inlet of the pipe as well  see photo. Outlet of pipe is severely bent and rusting right through.          ,"As there is not a lot of fill on this pipe, it seems very possible that a high flow event would result in water over top of the road          "," Because of fine substrate and documentation of low flows in the past, it seems unlikely that this stream supports fish.
